      "sl.reverse.fromSL`.  \n   Which is not generally true, but perhaps the issue is in the understanding of `fromSL`.  \n\n   Recheck the definitions:\n   - `List.toSL l = ⟨l, l.reverse⟩` (as per Lean docs)  \n   - `SymList.reverse ⟨as, bs⟩ = ⟨bs, as⟩`  \n   - `fromSL ⟨as, bs⟩ = as ++ bs`  \n   So for `sl = List.toSL l`, `sl.fromSL = l ++ l.reverse`.  \n   Then `sl.reverse.fromSL = l.reverse ++ l`.  \n   But `List.reverse sl.fromSL = (l ++ l.reverse).reverse = (l.reverse).reverse ++ l.reverse = l ++ l.reverse`.  \n   So the statement becomes `l ++ l.reverse = l.reverse ++ l`, which is false unless `l = []`.\n\n   But in the actual problem, it seems that `SymList.reverse` of `⟨a, b⟩` is `⟨b, a⟩`, and `fromSL ⟨a, b⟩ = a ++ b`, so the statement becomes `(a ++ b).reverse = b ++ a`.\n\n   However, `(a ++ b).reverse = b.reverse ++ a.reverse`, not `b ++ a`.  \n   So unless `a.reverse = a` and `b.reverse = b`, it doesn't hold.  \n   The claim is clearly false in general, so likely the user has made a mistake in their statement.\n\n   But perhaps the user meant `SymList.reverse` to be the actual reverse of the symmetric list.  \n   But `⟨a, b⟩.reverse = ⟨b, a⟩`, and the `fromSL` is `a ++ b`, so `(⟨a, b⟩.reverse).fromSL = b ++ a`.  \n   So `(a ++ b).reverse = b.reverse ++ a.reverse`, and we want to prove it is equal to `b ++ a`.  \n   But that would require `b.reverse ++ a.reverse = b ++ a`, which again is not general unless `a` and `b` are palindromes and `a.reverse = a` and `b.reverse = b`.\n\n   So the statement seems false unless further assumptions are made, but perhaps `SymList.reverse` is supposed to reverse the underlying list.  \n   But it is not, since it swaps `a` and `b`, but the `fromSL` would then give `a ++ b` reversed as `b.reverse ++ a.reverse`, not `b ++ a`.\n\n   But in Lean, the `reverse` for `SymList` is `⟨as, bs⟩.reverse = ⟨bs, as⟩`, and `fromSL ⟨as, bs⟩ = as ++ bs`.  \n   Thus, `(⟨as, bs⟩.reverse).fromSL = bs ++ as`.  \n   Also, `List.reverse (fromSL