rse, _⟩`\n   - `(List.toSL xs).reverse = ⟨xs.reverse, xs, _⟩`\n   - `(List.toSL xs).reverse.fromSL = xs`\n   - `(List.toSL xs).fromSL.reverse = xs.reverse.reverse = xs`\n   Then `List.toSL [1,2,3] |>.reverse |>.fromSL` would be `xs = [1,2,3]`, but the `#eval` gives `[3,2,1]`. \n\n   No. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps `List.toSL xs = ⟨xs.reverse, xs, _⟩`. \n\n   Then for `xs = [1,2,3]`, `List.toSL xs = ⟨[3,2,1], [1,2,3], _⟩`.\n   - Its reverse is `⟨[1,2,3], [3,2,1], _⟩`\n   - `fromSL` of that is `[3,2,1]` (if it takes the `right` component)\n   - Which matches `#eval`. \n\n   Now, `List.toSL xs = ⟨xs.reverse, xs, _⟩`, and `fromSL` takes the `right` component, then for general `sl = ⟨as, bs, h⟩`:\n   - `sl.fromSL = bs`\n   - `sl.reverse.fromSL = as`\n   - The goal becomes `bs.reverse = as`.\n\n   However, if `List.toSL xs = ⟨xs.reverse, xs, _⟩`, then `as = xs.reverse`, `bs = xs`, and indeed `bs.reverse = xs.reverse = as`. But for general `sl`, we would have `bs.reverse = as`, which cannot be deduced from `as.length = bs.length`. \n\n   So perhaps `SymList` is",
